{
  "files": [
    {"repo": "sg-evals/expressjs-express", "path": "lib/request.js"},
    {"repo": "sg-evals/expressjs-express", "path": "test/req.host.js"},
    {"repo": "sg-evals/expressjs-express", "path": "History.md"}
  ],
  "text": "The deprecated req.host property in Express.js is referenced in three key source files. First, the canonical definition is in lib/request.js (lines 452-456), where req.host is defined as a getter using deprecate.function() with the deprecation message 'req.host: Use req.hostname instead'. The implementation shows that req.host simply returns this.hostname, serving as an alias to the newer req.hostname property that was introduced as the correct replacement. Second, the comprehensive test suite for req.host is located in test/req.host.js, which contains multiple test cases verifying the deprecated property's behavior across various scenarios including handling of port numbers, IPv6 literals, and the trust proxy configuration. This test file specifically tests the deprecated req.host property (distinct from test/req.hostname.js which tests the replacement property). Third, the History.md changelog documents the deprecation history, including the formal deprecation notice in version 4.3.0 (lines 1284-1286) which states 'add req.hostname -- correct name for what req.host returns' and 'deprecate req.host -- use req.hostname instead'. Additional changelog entries document earlier features and fixes related to req.host, including the addition of req.host support (line 2726) and subsequent bug fixes for IPv6 literals (line 1436) and trust proxy behavior (line 799). These three files comprehensively document the deprecated req.host property from its original implementation through its formal deprecation in favor of req.hostname."
}

